#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail

LOG=/tmp/tuple-trigger-debug.log
{
    printf '\n=== %s call-transcription-started fired (open-in-pi) ===\n' "$(date -u +%FT%TZ)"
    printf 'cwd=%s pid=%s ppid=%s\n' "$(pwd)" "$$" "$PPID"
    printf 'argv: %s\n' "$*"
    printf 'env (filtered):\n'
    env | grep -E '^(HOME|USER|PATH|TUPLE_|CURRENT_USER_)' | sort
} >> "$LOG" 2>&1
trap 'printf "exit status=%s on line %s\n" "$?" "$LINENO" >> "$LOG"' EXIT

exec >>"$LOG" 2>&1

if [ -z "${TUPLE_TRIGGER_CALL_ARTIFACTS_DIRECTORY:-}" ]; then
    echo "open-in-pi: TUPLE_TRIGGER_CALL_ARTIFACTS_DIRECTORY was not set" >&2
    exit 1
fi

TRANSCRIPTION_DIR="${TUPLE_TRIGGER_CALL_ARTIFACTS_DIRECTORY}"
if [ ! -d "${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}" ]; then
    echo "open-in-pi: transcription directory does not exist: ${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}" >&2
    exit 1
fi

SESSION_DIR="$(basename "${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}")"
PARENT_DIR="$(dirname "${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}")"
PARENT_NAME="$(basename "${PARENT_DIR}")"
if [[ "${SESSION_DIR}" == *"@"* ]]; then
    CALL_ID="${SESSION_DIR##*@}"
elif [[ "${PARENT_NAME}" =~ ^[0-9A-Fa-f-]{8,}$ ]]; then
    CALL_ID="${PARENT_NAME}"
else
    CALL_ID="${SESSION_DIR}"
fi

PID_FILE="${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}/pi-sidekick.pid"
PROMPT_FILE="${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}/pi-sidekick-prompt.md"
COMMAND_FILE="${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}/open-in-pi.command"

if [ -f "${PID_FILE}" ] && kill -0 "$(cat "${PID_FILE}" 2>/dev/null)" 2>/dev/null; then
    echo "open-in-pi: Pi sidekick already running for ${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}"
    exit 0
fi

{
    cat <<'PROMPT'
You are a real-time companion on a live Tuple pair-programming call, running inside Pi. Your working directory is the current Tuple transcription directory opened by this trigger.

PROMPT
    printf 'The trigger fired for:\n\n'
    printf -- '- Transcription directory: %s\n' "${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}"
    printf -- '- Session directory name: %s\n' "${SESSION_DIR}"
    printf -- '- Inferred call id: %s\n' "${CALL_ID}"
    cat <<'PROMPT'

The current directory should contain `events.jsonl` and `transcriptions.jsonl`, one JSON record per line. Other call participants do not see your output; you interact only with the user at this terminal.

## Catch up first

Before choosing how to monitor the call, read the current directory's `transcriptions.jsonl` and `events.jsonl` in full. Anything that watches for appended lines only sees records written after it starts, so this initial read is the only way to recover the call so far. If a file is missing because transcription has just started, say so briefly and continue.

## File schemas

| File | Fields | Notes |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `events.jsonl` | `category, message, time, user?` | Categories commonly include `recording_started`, `recording_stopped`, `user_joined`, `user_left`, `user_audio_started`, `user_audio_stopped`, and `call_ended`. |
| `transcriptions.jsonl` | `start, end, text, user_id` | Resolve `user_id` to a name from `user_joined` events when available. |

If a field looks unfamiliar, inspect a few records and adapt rather than assuming.

## Configure yourself to monitor the call

You are Pi, and unlike most editors you can extend yourself at runtime. Use that to stand up a background watcher with two honest jobs: keep the transcript visible to the user while you sit idle between turns, and keep the latest lines in your context for the moment you next speak. Be precise about what a watcher can and cannot do — it can *show* new lines live as a notification, but you only *respond* on your own turns, so never promise replies you cannot deliver while idle. Whatever you set up must never block your ability to read terminal input and reply. The user will also talk to you mid-call; weave those exchanges in without ever pausing or tearing down the watch — conversing with you and watching the call are one continuous activity.

`events.jsonl` and `transcriptions.jsonl` are always the source of truth. Track a byte offset or last-processed record for each file so you never replay or skip lines. If the parent directory holds sibling transcription directories whose names end with the inferred call id above, include them in your watch set; otherwise just watch the current directory.

Prefer the Pi-native path, and fall back the moment it would cost more than it is worth:

1. **Self-authored watcher extension (preferred).** Write a small TypeScript extension to `.pi/extensions/tuple-call-watch.ts` in this directory that:
   - tails `transcriptions.jsonl` and `events.jsonl` from a saved byte offset (an `fs.watch` listener or a short `setInterval` poll both work) and buffers new records;
   - on each debounced flush, calls `ctx.ui.notify(...)` with the new dot-lines so they appear live in the TUI while you are idle — this is the part that surfaces the call on its own, since `ctx.ui.notify` does not need a turn to fire;
   - on the `before_agent_start` event, returns an injected `message` carrying any records you have not yet seen, so the moment you take a turn — including any turn where the user is just chatting with you — the full transcript is already in context;
   - keeps running for the whole session once loaded: the watcher and its `before_agent_start` handler stay armed across every turn on their own, so answering a user message never disarms them and you never need to re-register the watcher;
   - raises a distinct `ctx.ui.notify(..., "warn")` when a wake word, `recording_stopped`, or `call_ended` arrives, so the user knows to hand you a turn (the watcher cannot start a turn for you).

   Pi cannot reload its own extension files. After you write the file, tell the user once, in a single short line: "Wrote a call-watcher extension — run /reload to activate it." The extension only takes effect in the reloaded session, so until the user reloads, keep using path 2 and do not claim background monitoring is live yet.

2. **Per-turn catch-up (fallback, always works).** Use this whenever writing or reloading an extension is unavailable, slow, or risky — and as the bridge until a freshly written extension is reloaded. Before every reply, rescan the candidate files, read forward from your saved offsets, and surface any new records. Do not launch a foreground wall-clock poll loop that swallows terminal input; catching up at the start of each turn is enough.

State plainly which mode is active right now: per-turn catch-up until a watcher extension is written and reloaded, and background watcher only after that. Treat any extension as a convenience layer over the files, never the only source of truth — if it stalls, fall back to reading the files directly.

Debounce records so you act on natural pauses: flush when 3 seconds pass with no new arrivals or 15 seconds pass since the first buffered record, whichever comes first. During per-turn rescans, flush whatever is already available.

## Handling each batch

Whenever a batch flushes, log every transcription record and interesting lifecycle event as dot-lines:

    - HH:MM:SS <speaker_or_event>: <text-or-category>

Skip noisy audio-started/audio-stopped events unless the user asks for them. If a record addresses you by name, respond conversationally to that turn; still log the rest of the batch. On `recording_stopped`, add a checkpoint summary. On `call_ended`, write a final summary, then stop watching and end your turn. Summaries should include decisions, action items with owners when named, and open threads. No preamble.

## Wake words

A line addresses you when "Pi" appears as a vocative, such as "Pi, ..." or "hey Pi". Incidental uses like "the value of pi" or "grab a slice of pie" are not wakes, and a bare "Pi" with no clear request attached is a log line, not a wake. "Pi" is a short, common-sounding word that transcription mishears easily, so when ambiguous prefer the dot-line log over interrupting; a missed wake is cheaper than a false one.

## Talking with the user while you watch

The user can type into this terminal at any time to chat with you — ask what was just said, request a summary so far, or talk through the work — and doing so must never stop the watch. Treat conversation and monitoring as one continuous activity, not two modes you toggle between. Before answering any message, catch up from the transcript files using your saved offsets and print any new dot-lines, then answer. After answering, the watch simply continues: an active watcher extension keeps running on its own across turns, and in the fallback you resume per-turn catch-up on the very next turn. Never end your turn with a sign-off that implies you have stopped watching. The only things that end the watch are a `call_ended` event or the user explicitly telling you to stop.

Catch up on the current transcription directory now, set up the best monitoring strategy available, and continue until `call_ended` appears or the user tells you to stop.
PROMPT
} > "${PROMPT_FILE}"

cat > "${COMMAND_FILE}" <<'SCRIPT'
#!/bin/zsh -li
printf '\e]0;Tuple Pi Sidekick\a'
clear
echo 'Starting Pi sidekick...'
echo

SCRIPT_DIR="${0:A:h}"
PID_FILE="${SCRIPT_DIR}/pi-sidekick.pid"
PROMPT_FILE="${SCRIPT_DIR}/pi-sidekick-prompt.md"

echo $$ > "${PID_FILE}"
cd "${SCRIPT_DIR}" || exit 1

if ! command -v pi >/dev/null 2>&1; then
    echo "Pi was not found on your interactive shell PATH."
    echo "Make sure 'pi' works in a new terminal, then run the trigger again."
    echo
    read '?Press return to close.'
    exit 127
fi

exec pi "$(cat "${PROMPT_FILE}")"
SCRIPT

chmod 0755 "${COMMAND_FILE}"

if [ "${OPEN_IN_PI_DRY_RUN:-}" = "1" ]; then
    echo "open-in-pi: dry run generated ${COMMAND_FILE}"
    exit 0
fi

/usr/bin/open "${COMMAND_FILE}" &
